spec: ab3316
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 668 (ab3316): __ipow__, __ilshift__, __irshift__ dict-presence (in-place **=, <<=, >>=) for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__ipow__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __ipow__. In-place exponentiation (__ipow__, **=) is the augmented assignment variant of __pow__. abc types define no __pow__ (confirmed false in wave 660), so __ipow__ is equally absent. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no arithmetic semantics — ABC **= n is not a defined Python operation. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__); none of these capabilities involve in-place exponentiation. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __ipow__ — functions are callables and descriptors, not numeric types. f **= n is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "Key finding (__ilshift__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __ilshift__. In-place left shift (__ilshift__, <<=) is the augmented assignment variant of __lshift__. abc types define no __lshift__ (confirmed false in wave 660), so __ilshift__ is equally absent. abc.ABC has no integer or bitwise data model; ABC <<= n is not a defined Python expression. abc.ABCMeta's entire capability is in class-hierarchy machinery; in-place left shift is entirely absent. The function type does not define __ilshift__; f <<= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects."
    - "Key finding (__irshift__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __irshift__. In-place right shift (__irshift__, >>=) is the augmented assignment variant of __rshift__. abc types define no __rshift__ (confirmed false in wave 660), so __irshift__ is equally absent. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no bitwise or integer data model; ABC >>= n is not a defined Python expression. abc.ABCMeta handles abstract method tracking and class hierarchy; >>= has no meaning for metaclass objects. The function type does not define __irshift__; f >>= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern from wave 667 (__itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, and in-place augmented assignment dunder tested across 17 consecutive waves (652–668). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery, not operator overloading."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 668 (ab3316): __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __ipow__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__ipow__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __ipow__.
# In-place exponentiation (__ipow__, **=) is the augmented assignment variant
#   of __pow__. abc types define no __pow__ (wave 660), so __ipow__ is equally
#   absent.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no arithmetic
#   or numeric semantics. ABC **= n is not a defined Python operation; ABC has
#   no __ipow__ to serve as an implementation.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass
#   registration. In-place exponentiation has no role in ABCMeta's
#   responsibilities (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__).
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __ipow__. f **= n is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects. Functions are callables and descriptors with no
#   arithmetic or in-place augmented assignment data model.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3316.ipow:
  description: "abc types __ipow__ dict-presence checks; wave 668"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3316

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3316001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__ipow__"], false]
    - ["ab3316002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__ipow__"], false]
    - ["ab3316003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__ipow__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __ilshift__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__ilshift__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __ilshift__.
# In-place left shift (__ilshift__, <<=) is the augmented assignment variant
#   of __lshift__. abc types define no __lshift__ (wave 660), so __ilshift__
#   is equally absent.
# abc.ABC: no integer or bitwise data model; ABC <<= n is not a defined
#   Python expression. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no
#   state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __ilshift__ for in-place left shift. ABCMeta's
#   API surface (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__) has no
#   arithmetic, bitwise, or augmented assignment component.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __ilshift__. f <<= n is not a valid Python
#   expression for callable objects. The function type is tightly scoped to
#   its role as a callable descriptor with a display representation.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3316.ilshift:
  description: "abc types __ilshift__ dict-presence checks; wave 668"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3316

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3316004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__ilshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3316005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__ilshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3316006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__ilshift__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __irshift__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__irshift__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __irshift__.
# In-place right shift (__irshift__, >>=) is the augmented assignment variant
#   of __rshift__. abc types define no __rshift__ (wave 660), so __irshift__
#   is equally absent.
# abc.ABC: a pure abstract base class helper with no integer, bitwise, or
#   in-place arithmetic data model. ABC >>= n is not a defined Python expression.
# abc.ABCMeta: a powerful metaclass, but its entire power lies in class-hierarchy
#   machinery — not in operator overloading. ABCMeta >>= n is not a valid Python
#   expression.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __irshift__. Unlike integers, which use __rshift__
#   for bit manipulation, CPython's built-in function type has no __irshift__.
#   f >>= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3316.irshift:
  description: "abc types __irshift__ dict-presence checks; wave 668"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3316

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3316007", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__irshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3316008", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__irshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3316009", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__irshift__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __ipow__, __ilshift__, __irshift__ across all 3 abc subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 3 classes x 3 methods = 9 rows.
# __ipow__: false for all 3.
# __ilshift__: false for all 3.
# __irshift__: false for all 3.
# All 9 values are false.
# Continues the all-false pattern from wave 667 (__itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__).
# The function type profile across all waves tested:
#   true:  __get__ (652), __repr__ (655), __call__ (656)
#   false: __set__, __delete__, __hash__, __eq__, __bool__, __lt__, __le__, __gt__,
#          __ge__, __str__, __len__, __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__,
#          __contains__, __add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__,
#          __mod__, __pow__, __lshift__, __rshift__, __and__, __or__, __xor__,
#          __radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__,
#          __rpow__, __rlshift__, __rrshift__, __rand__, __ror__, __rxor__,
#          __iadd__, __isub__, __imul__, __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, __imod__,
#          __ipow__, __ilshift__, __irshift__
# The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor with
#   a display representation. All arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, and in-place
#   augmented assignment operators are absent.
# abc.ABCMeta note: ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic,
#   bitwise, reflected, and augmented assignment dunder tested across 17
#   consecutive waves (652–668). Its power lies exclusively in class-hierarchy
#   machinery — not in operator overloading of any kind.
# abc.ABC note: ABC is a pure syntactic convenience for declaring abstract base
#   classes. It has no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides, and defines
#   no arithmetic, bitwise, reflected arithmetic, power/shift, reflected bitwise
#   logical, or in-place augmented assignment protocol whatsoever.
# Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:
#   Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false.
#   Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false.
#   Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 668 (ab3316): __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — all false for all 3.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

